@anthares clearly has you covered for the NativeScript Core side of the question!

I&#39;ll cover the React NativeScript specifics.

Here is a [sample repo](https://github.com/shirakaba/tns-template-blank-react) (actually the repo for the React NativeScript starter template) showing how to integrate fonts into a React NativeScript app (it&#39;s probably no different than integrating fonts into a NativeScript Core app). I notice that you&#39;re using CSS, incidentally ‚Äì that repo also shows how to set up for SCSS.

`app/components/AppContainer.tsx` shows how to use glyph icons in React NativeScript:


```js
&lt;$Label row={0} col={0} className=&quot;info&quot; horizontalAlignment=&quot;center&quot; verticalAlignment=&quot;middle&quot;&gt;
    &lt;$FormattedString&gt;
        &lt;$Span className=&quot;fa&quot; text=&quot;&amp;#xf135;&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;$Span text=&quot; MESSAGE&quot;/&gt;
    &lt;/$FormattedString&gt;
&lt;/$Label&gt;
```

*EDIT: Note that the glyph icon needn&#39;t be inside a FormattedString Span. It could be written directly as `&lt;$Label text=&quot;&amp;#xf135;&quot;/&gt;`, and possibly also `&lt;$Label&gt;&amp;#xf135;&lt;/$Label&gt;` depending on how JSX works.*

That&#39;s how to write it as a **static** string in JSX, at least. If you write your `text` property as a **dynamic** string, however, i.e.:

```js
text={`Some dynamic string`}
```

... Then you may find that the escaping rules may be different (because it should follow the rules of regular JS syntax in that context). I&#39;d guess that it may behave like code-behind in that context.

Note: It may also be that `&amp;#xf135;` isn&#39;t the only way to write it in the static context. I just happened to copy-and-paste that from a NativeScript Vue example and it worked as-is, so I went with it.

